<TITLE> Hayden scores century as Australia consolidate </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Melbourne, Dec 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Opener Matthew Hayden scored his 28th test century as Australia consolidated their innings after losing three quick wickets in the session before tea on the first day of the first test against India on Wednesday. Hayden, who shared a 135-run opening partnership with Phil Jacques, was 121 not out with Michael Clarke on 14 as the home side reached the tea interval at 213 for three. India captain Anil Kumble took two wickets in the afternoon session as Australia suffered a mini-slump with three wickets falling for 30 runs. Resuming on 111 for no wicket with Hayden on 49 and Jacques on 57, the pair moved the score to 135 before Jacques was drawn down the wicket by a Kumble topspinner that was neatly taken by wicketkeeper Mahendra Dhoni, who whipped the bails off. Australia captain Ricky Ponting, who had won the toss and chosen to bat on the grassy pitch in perfect conditions, was then bowled by Zaheer Khan for four with a delivery that seamed just away to knock over off stump. Mike Hussey was then trapped in front by Kumble off another delivery that failed to spin for two, leaving the home side at 165 for three and in danger of undoing all the hard work from the morning session. However, Hayden, who had been circumspect before lunch but accelerated after the break, reached his century with a cover drive off Rudra Pratap Singh for his eighth boundary. Hayden and Clarke then consolidated the innings with their unbroken 48-run partnership. Kumble was the pick of the bowlers with figures of two for 46 off 14 overs at the brea
